Although they are often classified as a type of Bonneville Cutthroat Trout because the Bear River now is in the drainage of the Great Salt Lake,formerly the Bear River flowed into the Snake River,and hence the pacific, but was diverted into prehistoric Lake Bonneville by a lava flow 15,000 years ago or so. It has been shown through various genetic tests that the Bear River form of the "Bonneville" Cutthroat Trout are more similar to Yellowstone Cutthroat Trout than they are to other Cutthroats in the ancient lake Bonneville drainage,so really they are a type of Yellowstone Cutthroat Trout. But its also important to understand that the entire Bonneville basin is a sub-basin of the upper snake river,with periodic exchange of aquatic species during pluvial maximum.

This is a population of pure Bonneville Cutthroats that were intentionally stocked in the lakes, which probably had no fish before that because of waterfalls below the outlets. Some of the trout in this lake are huge for a high elevation lake, 18". They are not easy to catch, this fish was released back into the lake.
These trout were re-introduced into this lake and drainage, and are 100% genetically tested pure Bonnevilles. All of these trout were re-released back into the lake.

Must have washed down from the reservoir up Red Butte canyon? Same guy I caught the other day,I just had to go back and check on him and make sure he was OK, and sure enough he was. This area does not have the water quaility to support trout through the hot summer months.

The Bonnevilles in this stream have been re-introduced from a genetically tested 100% pure population, and all stocking of non-native have been discontinued. You can see from this male in spawning colors, these Bonneville's can be very colorful, and have large spots, making a rather striking trout.

Curious what the opinions are on this fish. Red Creek Reservoir has been stocked with a variety of triploid rainbow trout strains. Above the reservoir, Red Creek contains an introgressed cutthroat trout population with a mishmash of genetics (Yellowstone, Bonneville, and the watershed native Colorado River). This fish clearly has a very strange and sporadic spotting pattern reminiscent of cutthroat, but it clearly has many characteristics that make it look like a rainbow trout as well. There was also no slash underneath the jaw. So, what do you think? Weird hatchery rainbow, weird cutbow, or something else? Link example of one of the different types of rainbow trout stocked here

I like that I can use iNaturalist as a resource for my integrated science term project. So a few months ago my grade had started a project where you could either do a science fair or a term project, I chose the term project. In my term project I did a report on how the different genes affected the trout and would provide evidence to the public about the differences in the fish.
Between the two fish there were some major differences. First of all the dots on the fish have different colorations and on one the dots are only on the top half of the back and on the other one the dots go all the way down to the belly. Another difference is the overall coloration of the whole body. One is a yellow-ish while the other has more of a silver coloring to it. On one of the browns the dots go all the way to the eye and on the other they stop at the operculum (gill flap.) There were many differences but the biggest difference was the dots, they had different combinations and on one it had a few dots that were connected in a V and in a straight line. I Believe that it had a more silver look and would be more interesting to catch because of its V shaped spots.

Caught in the Santa Clara River. Based on the markings and location, I'm fairly confident this is a Colorado River Cutthroat, not a Bonneville. As far as I know, there are no records of cutthroat trout being stocked in this drainage, so I believe this may be a relic native population. On a solo camping Adventure in September 2024, I caught this Native Trout on an Elk Hair Caddis Fly. I used a Willow switch for a rod. I harvested it for my dinner. A very unique experience to catch a Trout in a red rock canyon! I was happy to observe a very healthy population of these fish, in South Ash Creek, after I helped the Utah DWR stock them here in the summer of 2019.
